'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].
== Descriptions in Historical Texts == The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命}}.
During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ}} demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.
== Genealogy == According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命}}. In the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀}}, the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include: - {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命}} - {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命}}, the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]]. - {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命}}
== Worship == Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Miho Shrine|ja|美保神社}} in {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|ja|島根県}}, {{ill|Nagata Shrine|ja|長田神社}} in {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸市}}, and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to {{ill|Ebisu|ja|えびす}}, such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社}} and {{ill|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|ja|今宮戎神社}}.
== Legends == === The Rooster Legend === In {{ill|Mihonoseki|ja|美保関町}}, a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.
=== Association with Izu === In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of {{ill|Mishima Taisha|ja|三嶋大社}} in the {{ill|Izu Peninsula|ja|伊豆半島}}, where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命}} as a god of island creation and fishing.
