'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神|12=draft}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].

== Descriptions in Historical Texts ==
The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定|12=draft}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ|12=draft}} demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎|12=draft}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.

== Genealogy ==
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|12=draft}}. In the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}}, the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神|12=draft}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include:
- {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|12=draft}}
- {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|12=draft}}, the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]].
- {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|12=draft}}

== Worship ==
Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Miho Shrine|ja|美保神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|ja|島根県|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagata Shrine|ja|長田神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸市|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft}}. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to {{ill|Ebisu|ja|えびす|12=draft}}, such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|ja|今宮戎神社|12=draft}}.

== Legends ==
=== The Rooster Legend ===
In {{ill|Mihonoseki|ja|美保関町|12=draft}}, a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫|12=draft}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.

=== Association with Izu ===
In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of {{ill|Mishima Taisha|ja|三嶋大社|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Izu Peninsula|ja|伊豆半島|12=draft}}, where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|12=draft}} as a god of island creation and fishing.

