'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi no Kami|qq=}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].

== Descriptions in Historical Texts ==
The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|qq=}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}} demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miho no Seki|qq=}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.

== Genealogy ==
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}. In the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Kuji Hongi|qq=}}, the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuhime no Kami|qq=}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include:
- {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushimikata no Mikoto|qq=}}
- {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|qq=}}, the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]].
- {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|qq=}}

== Worship ==
Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Miho Shrine|ja|美保神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miho Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|ja|島根県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimane Prefecture|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagata Shrine|ja|長田神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagata Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobe|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}}. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to {{ill|Ebisu|ja|えびす|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebisu|qq=}}, such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|ja|今宮戎神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|qq=}}.

== Legends ==
=== The Rooster Legend ===
In {{ill|Mihonoseki|ja|美保関町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihonoseki|qq=}}, a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihozuhime|qq=}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.

=== Association with Izu ===
In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of {{ill|Mishima Taisha|ja|三嶋大社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mishima Taisha|qq=}} in the {{ill|Izu Peninsula|ja|伊豆半島|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izu Peninsula|qq=}}, where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|qq=}} as a god of island creation and fishing.

