'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi no Kami|qq=}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].

== Descriptions in Historical Texts ==
The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the [[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]], Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|qq=}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when [[:en:Takemikazuchi|Takemikazuchi]] demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miho no Seki|qq=}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.

== Genealogy ==
According to the [[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]], Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}. In the [[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]], the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuhime no Kami|qq=}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include:
- {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushimikata no Mikoto|qq=}}
- {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|qq=}}, the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]].
- {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|qq=}}

== Worship ==
Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including [[:en:Miho Shrine|Miho Shrine]] in [[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]], [[:en:Nagata Shrine|Nagata Shrine]] in [[:en:Kobe|Kobe]], and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=}} in [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]]. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to [[:en:Ebisu (mythology)|Ebisu]], such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|qq=}} and [[:en:Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine]].

== Legends ==
=== The Rooster Legend ===
In [[:en:Mihonoseki, Shimane|Mihonoseki]], a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihozuhime|qq=}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.

=== Association with Izu ===
In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of [[:en:Mishima Taisha|Mishima Taisha]] in the [[:en:Izu Peninsula|Izu Peninsula]], where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|qq=}} as a god of island creation and fishing.

