{{short description|Shinto deity}}{{infobox deity | type = Shinto | children = [[Himetataraisuzu-hime]], [[Isuzuyori-hime]] | father = [[Ōkuninushi]] | consort = [[Tamakushi-hime]] | mother = [[Nunakawahime]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philippi |first1=Donald L. |title=Kojiki |date=2015 |publisher=Princeton University Press |pages=104–112}}</ref> {{ill|Tagitsuhime|ja|タギツヒメ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime|qq=}} }}
{{Nihongo|'''Kotoshironushi'''|事代主神}}, also known as {{Nihongo|'''Yae Kotoshironushi no kami'''|八重言代主神}}, is a [[Shinto]] ''[[kami]]''.
In the ''[[Kojiki]]'', Kotoshironushi is the son of [[Ōkuninushi]], the earthly deity of [[Izumo province]]. When the heavenly deities sent [[Takemikazuchi]] to conquer Izumo, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision over whether to resist to his two sons. Kotoshironushi, who had been fishing at the time of Takemikizuchi's arrival, agreed to accept the rule of the heavenly gods, surrendered his spear and left Izumo.<ref name="Kidder2007">{{cite book|author=Jonathan Edward Kidder|title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai: Archaeology, History, and Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7pEOicqsjv0C&pg=PA116|year=2007|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3035-9|page=116}}</ref> His brother [[Takeminakata]] fought with Takemikazuchi and was defeated.<ref name="Hackin1932">{{cite book|author=J. Hackin|title=Asiatic Mythology: A Detailed Description and Explanation of the Mythologies of All the Great Nations of Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAZrFhvqnTkC&pg=PA395|year=1932|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0920-4|page=395}}</ref>
Kotoshironushi is the principal deity of the [[Asuka Shrine|Asuka shrine]],<ref name="Ponsonby-Fane2014">{{cite book|author=R. A. B. Ponsonby-Fane|title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BY23AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA499|date=3 June 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-89294-3|pages=499–500}}</ref> and is associated with the god [[Ebisu (mythology)|Ebisu]].<ref name="HavensInoue2006">{{cite book|author1=Norman Havens|author2=Nobutaka Inoue|title=An Encyclopedia of Shinto (Shinto Jiten): Kami|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_YQAQAAIAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Institute for Japanese Culture and Classics Kokugakuin University|isbn=978-4-905853-08-4|page=88}}</ref> In mythology, he was an adviser to [[Empress Jingū]] during her invasion of [[Korea]]. He was also one of the eight deities charged with protecting the Imperial Court.<ref name="Aston2013">{{cite book|author=William Aston|title=Shinto (The Way of the Gods)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pOZRAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT172|date=11 December 2013|publisher=Adegi Graphics LLC|isbn=978-0-543-01408-5|page=172}}</ref> His daughter [[Himetataraisuzu-hime]] became the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Atsushi|first1=Kadoya|title=Kotoshironushi|url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=95|publisher=Encyclopedia of Shinto|access-date=14 September 2015}}</ref>
==Overview==
{{Infobox Japanese deity | image = Nagatajinjya0906.JPG | image_size = 260px | caption = {{Center|[[Nagata Shrine]] ([[:en:Nagata-ku, Kobe|Nagata-ku, Kobe]], [[:en:Kobe|Kobe]], Hyōgo Prefecture)}} | name = Kotoshironushi no Kami | type = {{ill|Kunitsukami|ja|国津神|1=Kunitsukami|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunitsukami|qq=}} | full_name = Kotoshironushi no Kami | other_names = Yaekotoshironushi no Kami, Yaegotoshironushi no Kami, Tamakushiiribiko Iwano Kotoshiro no Kami, Tumihayahie Kotoshironushi no Kami, Shiroshi Kotoshironushi no Kami, etc. | alternative_names = {{ill|Ebisu|ja|恵比寿大神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebisu|qq=}} | Rank = | nature = Oracle deity, Fishing deity, Crocodile deity | parents = Father: [[Ōkuninushi no Kami]]; Mother: {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}} ([[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]) or {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|湍津姫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuhime no Kami|qq=}} ([[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]]) | spouse = [[:en:Tamakushi-hime|Tamakushihime]], {{ill|Awame no Mikoto|ja|阿波咩命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awame no Mikoto|qq=}}, etc. | children = {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushimikata no Mikoto|qq=}}, {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|qq=}}, {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|qq=}}, etc. | shrines = [[:en:Miho Shrine|Miho Shrine]], {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=}}, [[:en:Nagata Shrine|Nagata Shrine]], etc. | related_clans = {{ill|Miwa clan|ja|三輪氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miwa clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Kamo no Asomi clan|ja|賀茂氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo no Asomi clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Munakata clan|ja|宗像氏|1=Munakata clan|fr|Clan Munakata|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Munakata clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Munakata clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagakuni no Miyatsuko|ja|長国造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagakuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}}, {{ill|Tosa no Miyatsuko|ja|都佐国造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tosa no Miyatsuko|qq=}}, {{ill|Hata clan|ja|波多国造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hata clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Ishibe clan|ja|石辺氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishibe clan|qq=}} }}
'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi no Kami|qq=}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].
== Descriptions in Historical Texts == The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the [[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]], Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}.
During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|qq=}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when [[:en:Takemikazuchi|Takemikazuchi]] demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miho no Seki|qq=}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.
== Genealogy == According to the [[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]], Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|qq=}}. In the [[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]], the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuhime no Kami|qq=}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include: - {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushimikata no Mikoto|qq=}} - {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|qq=}}, the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]]. - {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|qq=}}
== Worship == Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including [[:en:Miho Shrine|Miho Shrine]] in [[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]], [[:en:Nagata Shrine|Nagata Shrine]] in [[:en:Kobe|Kobe]], and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=}} in [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]]. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to [[:en:Ebisu (mythology)|Ebisu]], such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|qq=}} and [[:en:Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine]].
== Legends == === The Rooster Legend === In [[:en:Mihonoseki, Shimane|Mihonoseki]], a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihozuhime|qq=}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.
=== Association with Izu === In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of [[:en:Mishima Taisha|Mishima Taisha]] in the [[:en:Izu Peninsula|Izu Peninsula]], where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|qq=}} as a god of island creation and fishing.
