[[sn:Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto]]
[[ja:事代主]] [[en:Kotoshironushi]] [[ja:Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[fa:کوتوشیرونوشی]] [[fr:Kotoshironushi]] [[ko:고토시로누시]] [[ru:Котосиронуси]] [[simple:Kotoshironushi]] [[zh:事代主神]] [[Category:translated pages with valid en interwikis]] [[Category:Expanded Pages from Wikipedia]]

{{short description|Shinto deity}}{{infobox deity | type = Shinto | children = [[Himetataraisuzu-hime]], [[Isuzuyori-hime]] | father = [[Ōkuninushi]] | consort = [[Tamakushi-hime]] | mother = [[Nunakawahime]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philippi |first1=Donald L. |title=Kojiki |date=2015 |publisher=Princeton University Press |pages=104–112}}</ref> {{ill|Tagitsuhime|ja|タギツヒメ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime|qq=}} }}
{{Nihongo|'''Kotoshironushi'''|事代主神}}, also known as {{Nihongo|'''Yae Kotoshironushi no kami'''|八重言代主神}}, is a [[Shinto]] ''[[kami]]''.
In the ''[[Kojiki]]'', Kotoshironushi is the son of [[Ōkuninushi]], the earthly deity of [[Izumo province]]. When the heavenly deities sent [[Takemikazuchi]] to conquer Izumo, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision over whether to resist to his two sons. Kotoshironushi, who had been fishing at the time of Takemikizuchi's arrival, agreed to accept the rule of the heavenly gods, surrendered his spear and left Izumo.<ref name="Kidder2007">{{cite book|author=Jonathan Edward Kidder|title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai: Archaeology, History, and Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7pEOicqsjv0C&pg=PA116|year=2007|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3035-9|page=116}}</ref> His brother [[Takeminakata]] fought with Takemikazuchi and was defeated.<ref name="Hackin1932">{{cite book|author=J. Hackin|title=Asiatic Mythology: A Detailed Description and Explanation of the Mythologies of All the Great Nations of Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAZrFhvqnTkC&pg=PA395|year=1932|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0920-4|page=395}}</ref>
Kotoshironushi is the principal deity of the [[Asuka Shrine|Asuka shrine]],<ref name="Ponsonby-Fane2014">{{cite book|author=R. A. B. Ponsonby-Fane|title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BY23AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA499|date=3 June 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-89294-3|pages=499–500}}</ref> and is associated with the god [[:en:Ebisu (mythology)|Ebisu]].<ref name="HavensInoue2006">{{cite book|author1=Norman Havens|author2=Nobutaka Inoue|title=An Encyclopedia of Shinto (Shinto Jiten): Kami|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_YQAQAAIAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Institute for Japanese Culture and Classics Kokugakuin University|isbn=978-4-905853-08-4|page=88}}</ref> In mythology, he was an adviser to [[Empress Jingū]] during her invasion of [[Korea]]. He was also one of the eight deities charged with protecting the Imperial Court.<ref name="Aston2013">{{cite book|author=William Aston|title=Shinto (The Way of the Gods)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pOZRAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT172|date=11 December 2013|publisher=Adegi Graphics LLC|isbn=978-0-543-01408-5|page=172}}</ref> His daughter [[Himetataraisuzu-hime]] became the consort of [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Atsushi|first1=Kadoya|title=Kotoshironushi|url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=95|publisher=Encyclopedia of Shinto|access-date=14 September 2015}}</ref>
