'''Kotoshironushi no Kami''' ({{ill|Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja|事代主神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi no Kami|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 事代主|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q8009611}}) is a deity in [[Japanese mythology]].

== Descriptions in Historical Texts ==
The deity is also referred to as Yaegotoshironushi no Kami and Yaekotoshironushi no Kami. According to the {{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|qid=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神屋楯比売|1=Kamuyatate hime no mikoto|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q30935372}}.

During the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja|葦原中国平定|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashihara no Nakatsukuni Heitei|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 国譲り|1=Kuni-yuzuri|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11621119}} (the subjugation of Ashihara no Nakatsukuni), when {{ill|Takemikazuchi|en|Takemikazuchi|qid=Q1502690|qid=Q1502690|lt=Takemikazuchi|1=Takemikazuchi}} demanded that Ōkuninushi hand over his lands, Ōkuninushi deferred the decision to his son, Kotoshironushi. Takemikazuchi then went to {{ill|Miho no Seki|ja|美保ヶ崎|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miho no Seki|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, where Kotoshironushi agreed to relinquish the land. Following this, Kotoshironushi sank into the sea, symbolizing his retreat from worldly affairs.

== Genealogy ==
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|qid=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}}, Kotoshironushi is the child of [[Ōkuninushi]] and {{ill|Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja|神屋楯比売命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiya Tatehime no Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神屋楯比売|1=Kamuyatate hime no mikoto|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q30935372}}. In the {{ill|Kujiki|en|Kujiki|qid=Q2716751|lt=Sendai Kuji Hongi|1=Kujiki}}, the mother is listed as {{ill|Takatsuhime no Kami|ja|高津姫神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuhime no Kami|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. Kotoshironushi's offspring include:
- {{ill|Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja|櫛御方命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kushimikata no Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 鴨王 (上古)|1=Kamo no Okimi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q55809532}}
- {{ill|Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja|媛蹈鞴五十鈴媛命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime Tatara Isuzuhime no Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ヒメタタライスズヒメ|1=Himetataraisuzu-hime|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q5353793}}, the consort of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|en|Emperor Jimmu|qid=Q200188|lt=Emperor Jimmu|1=Emperor Jimmu}}.
- {{ill|Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja|五十鈴依姫命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isuzu Yorihime no Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 五十鈴依媛命|1=Isuzuyori-hime|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q10881557}}

== Worship ==
Kotoshironushi is enshrined in various shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Miho Shrine|en|Miho Shrine|qid=Q3313076|lt=Miho Shrine|1=Miho Shrine}} in {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|en|Shimane Prefecture|qid=Q132751|lt=Shimane Prefecture|1=Shimane Prefecture}}, {{ill|Nagata Shrine|en|Nagata Shrine|qid=Q661395|lt=Nagata Shrine|1=Nagata Shrine}} in {{ill|Kobe|en|Kobe|qid=Q48320|lt=Kobe|1=Kobe}}, and {{ill|Kamo Tsuba Shrine|ja|鴨都波神社|1=Kamo Tsuba Shrine|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Tsuba Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en|Nara Prefecture|qid=Q131287|lt=Nara Prefecture|1=Nara Prefecture}}. The deity is also celebrated at shrines dedicated to {{ill|Ebisu (mythology)|en|Ebisu (mythology)|qid=Q1129330|lt=Ebisu|1=Ebisu (mythology)}}, such as {{ill|Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|ja|京都ゑびす神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|1=Kyoto Ebisu Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q65248501}} and {{ill|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|en|Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|qid=Q11376859|lt=Imamiya Ebisu Shrine|1=Imamiya Ebisu Shrine}}.

== Legends ==
=== The Rooster Legend ===
In {{ill|Mihonoseki, Shimane|en|Mihonoseki, Shimane|qid=Q6845336|lt=Mihonoseki|1=Mihonoseki, Shimane}}, a legend states that Kotoshironushi despises roosters. According to the tale, Kotoshironushi visited {{ill|Mihozuhime|ja|美保津姫|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihozuhime|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 三穂津姫|1=Mihotsuhime-no-Mikoto|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q6378698}} nightly. One night, a rooster crowed prematurely, startling him, and he accidentally left his paddle behind. This led to an encounter with a crocodile (or shark), which bit his hand, causing him to resent roosters thereafter. This legend influences local customs, prohibiting the keeping of roosters or the consumption of eggs.

=== Association with Izu ===
In the modern period, Kotoshironushi is sometimes conflated with the deity of {{ill|Mishima Taisha|en|Mishima Taisha|qid=Q650772|lt=Mishima Taisha|1=Mishima Taisha}} in the {{ill|Izu Peninsula|en|Izu Peninsula|qid=Q822822|lt=Izu Peninsula|1=Izu Peninsula}}, where he is worshiped alongside {{ill|Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to オオヤマツミ}} as a god of island creation and fishing.

